================================================================================
  PROJECT OVERVIEW
================================================================================

This project is a suite of standalone PowerShell 5.1 graphical tools for
astronomical calculations. Each script provides a Windows Forms interface and
implements algorithms taken directly from peer-reviewed, published references,
with no third-party libraries required beyond what ships with Windows.

The suite covers the full chain of observational astronomy: time systems,
coordinate transformations, solar and lunar positions, lunar phase and
apogee/perigee events, solar and lunar eclipse predictions with local
circumstances, and planetary conjunction searches via a live NASA web API.

All scripts share the same design conventions:
  - Requires PowerShell 5.1 (#Requires -Version 5.1)
  - Add-Type for System.Windows.Forms and System.Drawing
  - EnableVisualStyles() for modern rendering
  - Arithmetic expressions pre-calculated before passing to Point/Size
    constructors (mandatory workaround for PS 5.1 parser limitations)
  - Pure ASCII output where displayed in fixed-width controls


================================================================================
  REFERENCES AND SOURCES
================================================================================

[1] Jean Meeus
    "Astronomical Algorithms", 2nd edition
    Willmann-Bell, Richmond VA, 1998
    --> Primary reference for all orbital mechanics, Julian Date arithmetic,
        sidereal time, obliquity of the ecliptic, Sun/Moon/planet positions,
        lunar phases (Ch. 32), lunar apogee and perigee (Ch. 47, 50),
        and eclipse theory.

[2] Jean Meeus
    "Astronomical Formulae for Calculators", 4th edition
    Willmann-Bell, Richmond VA, 1988
    --> Used specifically for sidereal time formulas (Ch. 7) and the
        equatorial <-> altitude-azimuth coordinate transformation (Ch. 8),
        and for lunar eclipse circumstances (Ch. 33).

[3] Fred Espenak & Jean Meeus
    "Five Millennium Canon of Solar Eclipses: -1999 to +3000"
    NASA Technical Publication TP-2009-214174
    NASA Special Publication   SP-2009-214173
    --> Source of the Besselian elements database included as the CSV file
        eclipse_besselian_from_mysqldump2.csv (~11,900 solar eclipses,
        54 columns per record). Used by EclissiCalc.ps1 to compute local
        eclipse circumstances with full Besselian element interpolation.

[4] JPL Horizons Web Service -- NASA Jet Propulsion Laboratory
    Endpoint: https://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/api/horizons.api
    Documentation: https://ssd-api.jpl.nasa.gov/doc/horizons.html
    --> Real-time ephemeris service queried by Horizons-Congiunzioni.ps1
        for observer-centric RA, Dec, magnitude, and angular diameter of
        solar-system bodies. Requires an active Internet connection.

[5] Astronomical Supplement (Explanatory Supplement to the Astronomical
    Almanac), Chapter 9
    --> Local solar eclipse circumstances algorithm:
        shadow-axis position x(t), y(t) in the fundamental plane,
        cone-axis declination d(t) and GHA mu(t), geocentric observer
        coordinates xi, eta, zeta, and magnitude formula
        (L1 - Delta) / (L1 + |L2|).


================================================================================
  SCRIPTS -- PURPOSE AND DETAILS
================================================================================

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  AstroCalc.ps1
  General Astronomical Calculator
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  Source  : Jean Meeus, "Astronomical Algorithms" (2nd ed.)

  Purpose :
    An all-in-one planetary calculator that computes positions and physical
    data for the Sun, the Moon, and all major planets as seen from a
    user-defined geographic location at any date and time.

  Capabilities :
    - Julian Date conversion for both Gregorian and Julian calendars
    - Greenwich Sidereal Time (GST) and Local Sidereal Time (LST)
    - Ecliptic obliquity for any epoch (with T^3 correction)
    - Kepler equation solver (iterative, convergence to 1e-10 rad)
    - True anomaly from eccentric anomaly
    - Sun: ecliptic longitude/latitude, RA/Dec, altitude/azimuth
    - Moon: RA/Dec, altitude/azimuth, phase angle, illuminated fraction
    - Planets (Mercury through Neptune): heliocentric orbital elements ->
      geocentric ecliptic -> equatorial (RA/Dec) -> local altitude/azimuth
    - Ecliptic-to-equatorial transformation (Ecl2Equ)
    - Altitude-azimuth calculation from hour angle (AltAz)
    - Output formatted as h m s  and  deg ' "

  Inputs  : Date (Y/M/D), UT time, observer latitude, observer longitude


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  FasiLunari.ps1
  Lunar Phases Calculator
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  Source  : Jean Meeus, "Astronomical Algorithms", Chapter 32

  Purpose :
    Calculates the exact dates and times of the four principal lunar phases
    -- New Moon, First Quarter, Full Moon, Last Quarter -- for any range of
    years, together with Moon rise, transit, and set for the observer.

  Capabilities :
    - Phase times in Terrestrial Dynamical Time (TD) and Universal Time (UT)
    - Delta-T (TD - UT) correction applied automatically
    - Local Mean Time (LMT) display derived from observer longitude
    - Moon rise, culmination (transit), and set times
    - Julian Day Number for each event
    - Multi-year search with scrollable tabular output
    - Export to clipboard or file

  Accuracy  : Phase times within ~1 minute over the range -2000 to +3000

  Inputs  : Start year, end year, observer latitude, observer longitude


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  LunaApogeoPerigeo.ps1
  Lunar Apogee and Perigee Calculator
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  Sources :
    Jean Meeus, "Astronomical Algorithms"
      Chapter 50 -- JDE of each apogee and perigee event
      Chapter 47 -- Earth-Moon distance (km)

  Purpose :
    Calculates the date, time, and Earth-Moon distance for every lunar
    apogee and perigee event within a user-specified year range.

  Capabilities :
    - Dates and times of every apogee and perigee (in UT)
    - Earth-Moon distance in kilometres for each event
    - Identification of "Super Moon" candidates (perigee coinciding
      with Full Moon within a configurable tolerance)
    - Multi-year tabular output

  Accuracy  : Date/time +/- 1-2 hours  |  Distance +/- 500-1500 km

  Inputs  : Start year, end year


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  EclissiCalc.ps1  (v4)
  Solar and Lunar Eclipse Calculator
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  Sources :
    [Solar]  Espenak & Meeus, Five Millennium Canon (NASA TP-2009-214174)
             -> Besselian elements from eclipse_besselian_from_mysqldump2.csv
             Explanatory Supplement, Ch. 9 -- local circumstances algorithm
    [Lunar]  Jean Meeus, "Astronomical Formulae for Calculators", Ch. 33
             + Moon altitude sampling over the event duration

  Purpose :
    The most comprehensive script in the suite. For solar eclipses it loads
    Besselian elements from the CSV database and computes exact local
    circumstances for the observer's site. For lunar eclipses it applies
    Meeus's analytical formulas plus altitude sampling.

  Solar eclipse local algorithm :
    x(t), y(t)    -- shadow axis position in the fundamental plane
    d(t), mu(t)   -- declination and GHA of the shadow cone axis
    xi, eta, zeta -- geocentric observer coordinates
    Delta         -- observer distance from the shadow axis
    Visibility condition : Delta <= L1(t)
    Local magnitude : (L1 - Delta) / (L1 + |L2|)

  Capabilities :
    - Search solar and/or lunar eclipses over any year range
    - For solar: eclipse type (Total, Annular, Hybrid, Partial), local
      contact times (C1 C2 C3 C4), local magnitude, path width, Sun Alt/Az
    - For lunar: penumbral, partial, and total phases with altitude
    - Saros series number and membership sequence
    - HTML report generation (landscape A4, ready for browser printing/PDF)
    - Results filterable by visibility at the observer's location

  Inputs  : Start year, end year, observer latitude, longitude, time zone


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  Horizons-Congiunzioni.ps1
  Planetary Conjunctions via JPL Horizons API
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  Source  : JPL Horizons Web API
            https://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/api/horizons.api
            (Internet connection required)

  Purpose :
    Searches for planetary conjunctions (minimum angular separation between
    any two solar-system bodies) visible above the horizon from the observer's
    location, by querying the NASA JPL Horizons ephemeris service.

  Bodies covered :
    Mercury (199), Venus (299), Moon (301), Mars (499), Jupiter (599),
    Saturn (699), Uranus (799), Neptune (899), Sun (10)

  API query parameters used :
    EPHEM_TYPE=OBSERVER, CENTER=coord@399, COORD_TYPE=GEODETIC,
    STEP_SIZE=1h, quantities: RA/Dec, magnitude, angular diameter

  Capabilities :
    - Configurable date range, observer site (lat/lon/elevation)
    - Selectable body pairs for conjunction search
    - Angular separation threshold filter
    - Altitude-above-horizon filter (objects must be visible)
    - Results displayed in a scrollable grid with export option
    - Cancellable background query with progress indicator

  Inputs  : Start date, end date, observer lat/lon/elev, body selection,
            max angular separation, min altitude


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  ConversioneCoordinate.ps1
  Equatorial <-> Altitude-Azimuth Coordinate Converter
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  Sources :
    Jean Meeus, "Astronomical Formulae for Calculators" (4th ed.)
      Chapter 7  -- Sidereal Time
      Chapter 8  -- Coordinate Transformation

  Purpose :
    Converts astronomical coordinates between the equatorial system
    (Right Ascension / Declination) and the horizontal system
    (Altitude / Azimuth) in both directions, for any date, time, and
    geographic location.

  Capabilities :
    - RA/Dec  ->  Alt/Az  (with atmospheric refraction option)
    - Alt/Az  ->  RA/Dec
    - Julian Date calculation (Get-JD)
    - Greenwich Sidereal Time and Local Sidereal Time
    - Hour angle computation
    - Normalisation functions Norm360 and Norm24
    - Input validation with user-friendly error messages
    - Results displayed in deg min sec and h m s notation

  Inputs  : Date (Y/M/D), UT time, observer latitude/longitude,
            RA + Dec  OR  Altitude + Azimuth


================================================================================
  DATA FILE
================================================================================

  eclipse_besselian_from_mysqldump2.csv
  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
  Rows    : ~11,900  (one row per solar eclipse)
  Columns : 54
  Period  : -1999 to +3000
  Origin  : Espenak & Meeus, Five Millennium Canon (NASA TP/SP 2009)
            exported from a MySQL database dump

  Key column groups :
    Date / time   : year, month, day, td_ge (TD of greatest eclipse)
    Identifiers   : luna_num, saros (Saros series), cat_no, canon_plate
    Eclipse type  : eclipse_type, etype (integer code), gamma, magnitude
    Geography     : lat_ge, lng_ge, lat_dd_ge, lng_dd_ge (greatest eclipse)
    Path geometry : path_width (km), central_duration, duration_secs,
                    sun_alt, sun_azm at greatest eclipse
    Besselian     : t0, tmin, tmax (time window in hours from greatest eclipse)
                    x0 x1 x2 x3  -- shadow axis X polynomial coefficients
                    y0 y1 y2 y3  -- shadow axis Y polynomial coefficients
                    d0 d1 d2     -- cone declination polynomial coefficients
                    mu0 mu1 mu2  -- GHA polynomial coefficients
                    l10 l11 l12  -- penumbral radius L1 polynomial coefficients
                    l20 l21 l22  -- umbral radius   L2 polynomial coefficients
                    tan_f1, tan_f2 -- half-angles of penumbral/umbral cones
    Saros info    : nSer, nSeq, nJLE (Saros sequence metadata)
    Category      : PNS, UNS, NCN  (eclipse category flags)
    Delta-T       : dt (seconds, TD - UT at greatest eclipse)
    Julian Date   : julian_date (JDE of greatest eclipse)

  Usage :
    Loaded at runtime by EclissiCalc.ps1. For each solar eclipse in the
    search range, the script reads the 12 Besselian polynomial coefficients
    and evaluates x(t), y(t), d(t), mu(t), L1(t), L2(t) at the observer's
    site to determine local visibility, contact times, and magnitude.


